  "local_port": 56712,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which country does the prime minister/president have the least power over the country?",
  "response": "The extent of power held by a prime minister or president varies significantly across countries, depending on the political system in place. In general, **ceremonial systems** or **parliamentary democracies** where the head of government or head of state holds symbolic or limited powers tend to have leaders with the least authority. Here are some examples:\n\n1. **Japan**  \n   - The **Prime Minister** is the head of government and holds significant executive power, but the **Emperor** is the symbolic head of state with no political authority.\n\n2. **United Kingdom**  \n   - The **Prime Minister** leads the government, but the **Monarch** (currently King Charles III) serves as the ceremonial head of state with no real political power.\n\n3. **Germany**  \n   - The **Federal Chancellor** (e.g., Olaf Scholz) is the head of government and wields significant executive power, while the **Federal President** (e.g., Frank-Walter Steinmeier) is a largely ceremonial figurehead.\n\n4. **India**  \n   - The **Prime Minister** (e.g., Narendra Modi) holds substantial executive power, while the **President** (e.g., Droupadi Murmu) serves as a ceremonial head of state.\n\n5. **Israel**  \n   - The **Prime Minister** (e.g., Benjamin Netanyahu) is the head of government with significant executive authority, while the **President** (e.g., Isaac Herzog) has a largely symbolic role.\n\n6. **Italy**  \n   - The **Prime Minister** leads the government, but the **President of the Republic** (e.g., Sergio Mattarella) holds a largely ceremonial role with limited powers.\n\n### Countries with the Least Executive Power\nIn **ceremonial systems**, the president or monarch typically has the least power, often limited to symbolic duties like signing legislation, representing the country, or appointing officials on the advice of the elected government. Examples include:\n\n- **Sweden**: The **Monarch** (King Carl XVI Gustaf) has no formal power, and the **Prime Minister** is the head of government.\n- **Norway**: The **Monarch** (King Harald V) is a ceremonial figure, while the **Prime Minister** holds executive power.\n- **Iceland**: The **President** is primarily a ceremonial role, and the **Prime Minister** holds executive authority.\n\nIn these countries, the real power lies with the parliament and the prime minister, while the president or monarch has minimal influence over governance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
